<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910823-0034</DOCNO><DOCID>910823-0034.</DOCID><HL>   Toppan to Combine Operations</HL><DATE>08/23/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B3A</SO><CO>   J.TAP</CO><MS>FINANCIAL (FIN)INDUSTRIAL (IDU)</MS><IN>INDUSTRIAL andamp; COMMERCIAL SERVICES, LEASING, CLEANING (ICS)REAL ESTATE INVESTMENTS (REA)INDUSTRIAL AND COMMERCIAL SERVICES (SVC)</IN><RE>FAR EAST (FE)JAPAN (JA)NEW JERSEY (NJ)NORTH AMERICA (NME)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   TOKYO -- Japan's Toppan Printing Co. has purchased a $14million factory site and building in Franklin Township, NewJersey, to combine its New Jersey prepress and printingoperations, a Toppan spokesman said Thursday.   Through the move, the company hopes to double its NewJersey commercial printing sales to $40 million in fiscal1992 beginning April 1, from the $20 million in revenue itpredicts for fiscal 1991, the spokesman said.</LP><TEXT>   The company will close its two existing factories in NewJersey and transfer their equipment to the new, 18,000square-meter facility, which is slated to begin operating inthe spring of next year. In addition to the $14 million spentfor the land and building, $6 million has been transferred tothe company's U.S. subsidiary to take care of moving costsand future purchases of equipment.   New York-based Toppan Printing Co. (America Inc.) has beenproducing brochures, posters and other commercial printedmaterial in New Jersey since 1974. It also operates threeother printing facilities in Georgia and California.</TEXT></DOC>